================================================================================
PLAN T016: 3 ALTERNATIVES FOR VISUAL 3D ASSET PREVIEW IN SETTINGS
================================================================================

This document details three alternative architectures to replace the simple text-based 
mascot dropdown with a visual selection interface that displays a 3D or 2D preview 
of the custom mascot models.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ALTERNATIVE 1: DYNAMIC SECONDARY WEBGL VIEWPORT (LIVE 3D PREVIEW PANEL)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Render each model in real-time inside a small sub-canvas in the settings panel 
before the user applies and saves the selection.

* Implementation Details:
  1. Add a small preview container `<div id="preview-viewport">` inside 
     [index.html](file:///c:/Users/space/.gemini/antigravity-ide/scratch/desktop-pet/index.html) settings panel.
  2. In [renderer.js](file:///c:/Users/space/.gemini/antigravity-ide/scratch/desktop-pet/renderer.js), instantiate an isolated secondary Three.js scene:
     - `previewScene = new THREE.Scene();`
     - `previewCamera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(...);`
     - `previewRenderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer({ alpha: true, antialias: true });`
  3. Bind a listener to selection hover/change events. When hovered, load the 
     corresponding `.glb` file using `GLTFLoader` into `previewScene`.
  4. Run a separate micro-render loop updating the rotation of `previewScene` 
     model meshes at 30fps inside the viewport bounds.
* Pros:
  - Displays fully interactive, animated, high-fidelity 3D visuals of the mascot.
  - Shows exactly how the model will look when deployed.
* Cons:
  - Higher performance penalty: running two WebGL contexts simultaneously can 
    increase CPU/GPU usage.
  - Slower initial loading times for heavy models.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ALTERNATIVE 2: AUTOMATIC STATIC THUMBNAIL CACHING (SCREENSHOT CAPTURE)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Automatically capture and cache a PNG thumbnail of the model when it is first 
loaded or dropped, and display a visual grid of cards in the settings panel.

* Implementation Details:
  1. Create a hidden subdirectory in the assets folder `assets/.previews/`.
  2. Replace the dropdown `<select>` element in [index.html](file:///c:/Users/space/.gemini/antigravity-ide/scratch/desktop-pet/index.html) with a card grid 
     container `<div class="mascot-grid">`.
  3. When a custom model is loaded in `loadCustomModel()` in [renderer.js](file:///c:/Users/space/.gemini/antigravity-ide/scratch/desktop-pet/renderer.js), 
     check if `assets/.previews/<modelname>.png` already exists.
  4. If not, render the model, hide UI overlays for one frame, grab the base64 data 
     via `renderer.domElement.toDataURL("image/png")`, and save it to the cache directory 
     using Node `fs.writeFileSync()`.
  5. Render the settings panel using a grid of cards pointing to the static `.png` images.
* Pros:
  - Extremely lightweight: zero runtime WebGL overhead since it displays standard `<img>` tags.
  - Visually modern grid layout that displays all custom pets at a single glance.
* Cons:
  - Requires maintaining a preview cache folder.
  - The first-time generation of the thumbnail requires loading the model once.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ALTERNATIVE 3: MOD-STYLE COMPANION ASSET LOADER (MANUAL IMAGES / PLACEHOLDERS)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Use companion image files stored next to the 3D models (a standard in mod packs and 
Steam Workshop items, e.g., `companion.glb` and `companion.png`).

* Implementation Details:
  1. In `scanForModels()` in [renderer.js](file:///c:/Users/space/.gemini/antigravity-ide/scratch/desktop-pet/renderer.js), look for a matching image file name 
     (e.g., if `rabbit.glb` is scanned, check if `rabbit.png`, `rabbit.jpg`, or `rabbit.webp` 
     exists in the same directory).
  2. If a companion image exists, use it as the source for card thumbnails in 
     the settings panel grid.
  3. If missing, fall back to showing a generic placeholder image (such as the default 
     pink bunny mascot graphic).
  4. Add a "Capture Current View as Icon" button inside settings, allowing users 
     to generate the companion image manually.
* Pros:
  - Safest performance profile: zero automatic renderer hooks needed.
  - Matches standard Steam Workshop asset directory packaging structures.
* Cons:
  - Users must manually provide thumbnails, or settle for placeholder graphics 
    for custom `.glb` files that lack companion images.
